  },
  "name": "Yoga: Body as Temple",
  "description": "A grammar of yoga as embodied philosophy — from individual asanas to the eight limbs of Patanjali. Each pose carries its Sanskrit story, its physical opening, and its place in a 5,000-year tradition of using the body as an instrument of awareness. Covers ~50 asanas across 7 families, the 8 limbs of classical yoga, and 3 meta-perspectives on what yoga is and where it's going.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Illustrations from early 20th-century translations of the Hatha Yoga Pradipika. Woodcuts from the Yoga Korunta tradition. Indian miniature paintings depicting yogic postures (Mughal and Rajput schools, 17th-18th century).",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
  "tags": ["yoga", "embodiment", "india", "sanskrit", "asana", "meditation", "philosophy", "contemplative-practice", "breath"],
  "roots": ["eastern-wisdom", "embodiment"],
  "shelves": ["wisdom", "earth"],
  "lineages": ["Shrei", "Linehan"],
  "worldview": "non-dual",
